<h2 class="text-center my-4">Gastropods of Tubbataha Reef</h2>

<div class="text-center mb-4">
    <img src="https://c8.alamy.com/comp/2FFTCPC/sea-slug-or-nudibranch-chromodoris-lochi-anilao-batangas-philippines-pacific-2FFTCPC.jpg" alt="Gastropods of Tubbataha Reef" class="img-fluid img-thumbnail" style="max-width: 65%; height: auto;" />
</div>

<p class="mb-4">
    Gastropods are a diverse group of mollusks that include snails, slugs, limpets, and nudibranchs (sea slugs). They play critical roles in the Tubbataha Reef ecosystem, contributing to biodiversity and ecological balance. The reef is home to an array of gastropod species, ranging from colorful nudibranchs to intricately designed cone snails.
</p>

<h3 class="text-center">Common Gastropods in Tubbataha Reef</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Nudibranchs (Sea Slugs)</h4>
    <ul>
        <div class="text-center mb-4">
            <img src="https://c8.alamy.com/comp/J7JJNM/close-up-image-of-nudibranch-chromodoris-lochi-J7JJNM.jpg" alt="Nudibranch" class="img-fluid img-thumbnail" style="max-width: 70%; height: auto;" />
        </div>
        <li><strong>Chromodoris annae:</strong> Vibrant blue, yellow, and black nudibranch.</li>
        <li><strong>Glossodoris cincta:</strong> Features fringed edges with colorful markings.</li>
        <li><strong>Flabellina species:</strong> Characterized by their cerata (finger-like appendages).</li>
        <li>Nudibranchs are often referred to as the "butterflies of the sea" due to their stunning patterns.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Cone Snails (Conidae)</h4>
    <p>Venomous predatory snails that use a specialized radula to hunt small fish and mollusks. Their shells are prized for their unique patterns but should not be handled due to their potent venom.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Cowries (Cypraeidae)</h4>
    <p>Known for their smooth, shiny, and colorful shells, often seen grazing on algae and detritus.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Tiger Cowry (Cypraea tigris):</strong> One of the largest and most recognizable species.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Top Snails (Trochidae)</h4>
    <p>Herbivorous snails with a conical shell, grazing on algae that grows on coral reefs.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Limpets</h4>
    <p>Marine snails with simple, cone-shaped shells that cling to rocks and reef surfaces.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">6. Tun Shells (Tonnidae)</h4>
    <p>Large predatory snails that feed on echinoderms like sea cucumbers.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">7. Murex Snails (Muricidae)</h4>
    <p>Known for their spiny, ornate shells; these predatory snails feed on bivalves and other mollusks.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Interesting Facts About Gastropods</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Incredible Diversity</h4>
    <p>Gastropods are among the most diverse groups of marine organisms, with species adapted to various habitats.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Unique Defense Mechanisms</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Nudibranchs:</strong> Use toxins from prey or aposematic coloration to deter predators.</li>
        <li><strong>Cone Snails:</strong> Deliver venom through a harpoon-like structure to paralyze prey instantly.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Ecological Roles</h4>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Grazers like cowries and limpets:</strong> Help control algae growth, maintaining coral health.</li>
        <li><strong>Predatory gastropods:</strong> Regulate populations of smaller invertebrates.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Bioactive Compounds</h4>
    <p>Cone snail venom contains compounds with medical potential, used in painkillers and other drugs.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Shell Formation</h4>
    <p>Their shells are made of calcium carbonate and are intricately designed, often used for identification.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Conservation Practices to Protect Gastropods</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Avoid Collecting Shells</h4>
    <p>Removing gastropods or their shells from the reef disrupts the ecosystem and reduces biodiversity.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Practice Ethical Snorkeling and Diving</h4>
    <p>Avoid touching or disturbing gastropods, as some (like cone snails) can be dangerous, and others are fragile.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Reduce Plastic Pollution</h4>
    <p>Plastics can harm or kill gastropods that ingest or become entangled in debris.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Support Sustainable Tourism</h4>
    <p>Choose eco-certified operators that promote conservation-focused marine activities.</p>
</section>

<h3 class="text-center my-4">Threats to Gastropods in Tubbataha Reef</h3>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">1. Climate Change</h4>
    <p>Ocean warming and acidification disrupt shell formation and habitats.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">2. Shell Collection</h4>
    <p>Overharvesting for souvenirs and the shell trade depletes gastropod populations.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">3. Pollution</h4>
    <p>Plastic waste, chemicals, and sediments damage reef habitats and harm gastropods.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">4. Habitat Destruction</h4>
    <p>Destructive fishing practices like dynamite fishing can decimate reef ecosystems.</p>
</section>

<section class="mb-4">
    <h4 class="text-primary">5. Coral Bleaching</h4>
    <p>Loss of coral habitat reduces food and shelter for reef-dwelling gastropods.</p>
</section>

